The great vowel shift happened is a period of time between 1400-1700 where the pronunciation of vowels and other letter changed the overall sound of the language.

| Today’s Word | Pronunciation before the Great Vowel Shift |
| ------------ | ------------------------------------------ |
| Goose        | “goas” (oa as in boat)                     |
| Mine         | “meen”                                     |
| Mice         | “mees”                                     |
| Shire        | “sheer”                                    |
| Sheep        | “shape”                                    |
| House        | “hoos”                                     |
| Life         | “leef”                                     |
| Flour        | “floor”                                    |
| Boot         | “boat”                                     |
| Mate         | “maat”                                     |
| Name         | “nahm”                                     |
| Feet         | “fayt” (ay as in “pay”)                    | 

In terms of phonology- vowels slowly changed from being pronounced at the front of the mouth and shifted upwards to the back of the mouth.

![See the source image](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

Although it is clearly apparent this transition occurred in English, there is an uncertainty as to why exactly. More than likely there are many reasons:

The Black Death- the plague forced migration and clashing of dialects within the country

A reaction to ‘French’ pronunciation of words

Influence of loan words from French

Whatever the reasons, the transition was a slow process.

Besides the Great Vowel Shift, the standardisation of language occurred due to many factors. Mass printing had a direct effect on the consistency of language use, including capitalising letters at the beginning of sentences.

Shakespeare’s main influence on language is through his vocabulary. Although he did coin many words and phrases, many of his works were the first to publish specific words and therefore solidify their use in English. In total, his works cover twenty thousand words- an average vocabulary is ten thousand.

He used affixes (both prefixes and suffixes) to enhance meaning – Bloody, Dateless, Temperate, Beauteous and he also used many compound nouns to broaden meaning- Bedroom, Eyelid.
